The `equ` is an `equiv` relation between two pairs: `(S, S_a)` and `(T, T_a)`, where `S_a` is the result set of `S` after the call `C`, and `T_a` is the result set of `T` after the call `C`. The `equiv` relation means that these two pairs are "indistinguishable" to agent `a`.

The key insight is that if two processes are indistinguishable to an agent, then the agent's knowledge about the world must be the same for both processes. In particular, if `S` leads to the agent knowing a fact `P`, then `T` must also lead to the agent knowing `P`.

From `h_b : @S b = true`, we know that for the first process `S`, the value of `b` (with respect to `S`'s internal state) is `true`. Since `a` is the caller, `a` is involved in the call `C` with `b`, so `a`'s knowledge about `b`'s value is relevant.

The `equiv` relation `equ` states that `(S, S_a)` and `(T, T_a)` are indistinguishable to `a`. This means that `a` cannot tell the difference between the two scenarios.

Since `a` is involved in the call `C` (as a `Caller`), `a` is directly affected by the outcome of the call. The fact that `a` is a `Caller` in `C` is given by `role_C : Error.Role.Caller = Error.roleOfIn n a C`.

The proof needs to show that `a`'s knowledge of `b`'s value must be the same in both scenarios. Since `a` is a `Caller`, `a` will have the same set of information available as `b` (the called agent) does.

The strategy is to use the `equiv` relation. The `equiv` relation implies that any property that holds for one pair must hold for the other pair.

In particular, the fact `@S b = true` (which is `h_b`) must imply `@T b = true`.

This is because the property `X ∈ S_a` (i.e., `X` is in the result set of `S` after the call) is equivalent to `X ∈ T_a` (i.e., `X` is in the result set of `T` after the call) if `(S, S_a)` and `(T, T_a)` are equivalent.

We need to show that `@T b = true`.

We can use the fact that `h_b : @S b = true` and `equ` implies `@T b = true`.

The property `@S b = true` is equivalent to `(⟨b, true⟩ ∈ S⌈σ⌉a)`. This is because `eval S ⟨σ, o⟩ (Kv a b)` is equivalent to `(⟨b, true⟩ ∈ S⌈σ⌉a)`.

Similarly, `@T b = true` is equivalent to `(⟨b, true⟩ ∈ T⌈τ⌉a)`.

The `equiv` relation `equ` states that `S⌈σ⌉a = T⌈τ⌉a`.

So, if `⟨b, true⟩ ∈ S⌈σ⌉a`, then `⟨b, true⟩ ∈ T⌈τ⌉a`.

This means `@T b = true`.

